snippet.textDisplay:
It's past time for the guy asking the questions to be replaced. He's out of touch with the culture and his questions feel very disjointed, like a paparazzi and not someone who wants to facilitate an authentic conversation. It feels like he can't read the room and he doesn't really know how to talk to these guys.

You can tell at times the actors are very caught off guard by his questions or by the way he asks them and then THEY have to try to patch up the awkwardness of it (which, to be crystal clear, is HIS job). At this specific roundtable, the actors eventually just give up trying to establish a "flow" because he's not willing to talk to them like PEOPLE instead of actors.

THR: You had an insanely good opportunity here and you blew it. If you need an example of an emotionally intelligent moderator in these situations, watch Off Camera. That guy does a fantastic job. In fact, you would do well to hire him as a replacement.
